{"time": "2016-09-05T12:31:19.576074", "block": {"tests_archive": null, "animation": null, "feedback_correct": "", "subtitles": {}, "source": null, "text": "<p>As we mentioned, our goal now is to figure out how we can <i>minimize</i> the expected number of collisions. To do so, we must turn to probability to begin to figure out how to even calculate the probability of encountering a collision in the first place. <br></p><p>To analyze the probability of collisions, we will use this basic identity from elementary probability to simplify our computation:</p><p class=\"wysiwyg-text-align-center\">$P(event)=1\u2212P(no\\ event)$\u00a0</p><p>The identity above can be read as \"the probability of an event occurring is the same as 1 minus the probability of the event <i>not</i> occurring.\" The basic idea surrounding this identity is that, at the end of the day, there is a 100% chance that an event either will or will not occur (i.e., $P(event) + P(no\\ event) = 1$). Consequently, we will say that,\n\nfor a <b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">Hash Table</span></b>\u00a0with <i>M </i>slots and <i>N </i>keys, the probability of seeing at least one collision is $P_{N,M}(\\ge 1\\ collision)=1\u2212P_{N,M}(no\\ collision)$. For our purposes, we will assume that all slots of the\u00a0<b><span class=\"wysiwyg-color-purple\">Hash Table</span></b> are equally likely to be chosen for an insertion of some arbitrary key.</p>", "options": {}, "subtitle_files": [], "name": "text", "video": null, "feedback_wrong": ""}, "id": "122016"}